2. Cycle-Based Yield Optimization Strategy

Best For: Users who want to adjust staking amounts based on dilution risk.

How It Works:
âœ… Monitor network-wide staked L1 at the start of each cycle.
âœ… If staking participation is low, stake more aggressively for higher rewards.
âœ… If staking participation is high, stake conservatively to reduce dilution impact.

Implementation:
Â Â Â â€¢Â Â Â Early in the cycle, if total staked L1 is low, commit longer-duration stakes for maximum yield.
Â Â Â â€¢Â Â Â Mid to late cycle, if total staked L1 is high, use shorter-duration stakes (90-180 days) to avoid dilution.
Â Â Â â€¢Â Â Â Adjust stake amounts each quarter based on the previous cycleâ€™s staking trends.

Example Adjustment Based on Dilution Risk:

Cycle Start (Day 1)	Total Staked L1	Staking Decision
Low Staked L1 (e.g., <10M L1)	Stake maximum for 365 days	Less competition = higher RL1 yield
Moderate Staked L1 (e.g., 10M-30M L1)	Split stakes (365 + 180 days)	Balanced approach
High Staked L1 (e.g., 30M+ L1)	Use rolling stakes (180-90 days)	Avoid dilution & maintain flexibility

ğŸ”¹ Result: Maximized RL1 earnings while avoiding over-dilution from late-cycle stakes.

